<H3>1.&nbsp;Introduction</H3>
<P>This memo describes how to write a document for the I-D and RFC =
series using=20
<A href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#XML">the =

Extensible Markup Language</A>[1] (XML). This memo has three goals:=20
<OL class=3Dtext>
  <LI>To describe a simple XML Document Type Definition (DTD) that is =
powerful=20
  enough to handle the simple formatting requirements of RFC-like =
documents=20
  whilst allowing for meaningful markup of descriptive qualities.=20
  <LI>To describe software that processes XML source files, including a =
tool=20
  that produces documents conforming to <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#refs.RFC2223=
">RFC=20
  2223</A>[2], HTML format, and so on.=20
  <LI>To provide the proof-of-concept for the first two goals (this memo =
was=20
  written using this DTD and produced using that software). </LI></OL>
<P></P>
<P>It is beyond the scope of this memo to discuss the political =
ramifications of=20
using XML as a source format for RFC-like documents. Rather, it is =
simply noted=20
that adding minimal markup to plain text:=20
<UL class=3Dtext>
  <LI>allows the traditional production of textual RFC-like documents =
using=20
  familiar editors;=20
  <LI>requires some, albeit minimal, additions to existing software=20
  environments; and,=20
  <LI>permits information to be organized, searched, and retrieved using =
both=20
  unstructured and structured mechanisms. </LI></UL>
<P></P><A name=3Danchor2><BR>
<HR SIZE=3D1 shade=3D"0">
</A>
