<H3>2.&nbsp;Using the DTD to Write I-Ds and RFCs</H3>
<P>We do not provide a formal or comprehensive description of XML. =
Rather, this=20
section discusses just enough XML to use a Document Type Declaration =
(DTD) to=20
write RFC-like documents. </P>
<P>If you're already familiar with XML, skip to <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#rfc.dtd">The=
 RFC=20
DTD</A> to look at the DTD. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dxml_basics>2.1</A>&nbsp;XML basics</H4>
<P>There are very few rules when writing in XML, as the syntax is =
simple. There=20
are five terms you'll need to know:=20
<OL class=3Dtext>
  <LI>An "element" usually refers to a start tag, an end tag, and all =
the=20
  characters in between, e.g., "&lt;example&gt;text and/or nested=20
  elements&lt;/example&gt;"=20
  <LI>An "empty element" combines the start tag and the end tag, e.g.,=20
  "&lt;empty/&gt;". You don't find these in HTML.=20
  <LI>An "attribute" is part of an element. If present, they occur in =
the start=20
  tag, e.g., "&lt;example name=3D'value'&gt;". Of course, they can also =
appear in=20
  empty elements, e.g., "&lt;empty name=3D'value'/&gt;".=20
  <LI>An "entity" is a textual macro that starts with "&amp;". Don't =
worry about=20
  these, you'll only use them whenever you want to put a "&amp;" or a =
"&lt;" in=20
  your text.=20
  <LI>A "token" is a string of characters. The first character is either =
a=20
  letter or an underscore ("_"). Any characters that follow are either =
letters,=20
  numbers, an underscore, or a period ("."). </LI></OL>
<P></P>
<P>First, start your source file with an XML declaration, a reference to =
the=20
DTD, and the "rfc" element: </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;?xml =
version=3D"1.0"?&gt;
    &lt;!DOCTYPE rfc SYSTEM "rfc2629.dtd"&gt;
    &lt;rfc&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/rfc&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>Ignore the first two lines -- the declaration and the reference -- =
and simply=20
treat them as opaque strings. Nothing else should be present after the=20
"&lt;/rfc&gt;" tag. </P>
<P>Second, make sure that all elements are properly matched and nested. =
A=20
properly matched element that starts with "&lt;example&gt;" is =
eventually=20
followed with "&lt;/example&gt;". (Empty elements are always matched.) =
Elements=20
are properly nested when they don't overlap. </P>
<P>For example, </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;outer&gt;
        ...
        &lt;inner&gt;
            ...
        &lt;/inner&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/outer&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>is properly nested. </P>
<P>However, </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;outer&gt;
        ...
        &lt;inner&gt;
            ...
        &lt;/outer&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/inner&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>overlaps, so the elements aren't properly nested. </P>
<P>Third, never use "&lt;" or "&amp;" in your text. Instead, use either=20
"&amp;lt;" or "&amp;amp;", respectively. </P>
<P>Fourth, there are two quoting characters in XML, 'apostrophe' and=20
"quotation". Make sure that all attributes values are quoted, e.g., =
"&lt;example=20
name=3D'value'&gt;", If the value contains one of the quoting =
characters, then use=20
the other to quote the value, e.g., "&lt;example name=3D'"'&gt;", If the =
value=20
contains both quoting characters, then use one of them to quote the =
value, and=20
replace occurrances of that character in the attribute value with either =

'&amp;apos;' (apostrophe) or "&amp;quot;" (quotation), e.g., =
"&lt;example=20
name=3D'"&amp;apos;"'&gt;". </P>
<P>If you want to put a comment in your source file, here's the syntax:=20
</P></FONT><PRE>        &lt;!-- comments can be multiline,
         if you wish --&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>Finally, XML is case sensitive. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dfront_matter>2.2</A>&nbsp;Front matter</H4>
<P>Immediately following the "&lt;rfc&gt;" tag is the "front" element:=20
</P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;?xml version=3D"1.0"?&gt;
    &lt;!DOCTYPE rfc SYSTEM "rfc2629.dtd"&gt;
    &lt;rfc&gt;
        &lt;front&gt;
            &lt;title ...&gt;
            &lt;author ...&gt;
            &lt;author ...&gt;
            &lt;date ...&gt;
            &lt;area ...&gt;
            &lt;workgroup ...&gt;
            &lt;keyword ...&gt;
            &lt;keyword ...&gt;
            &lt;abstract ...&gt;
            &lt;note ...&gt;
        &lt;/front&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/rfc&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>(Note that in all examples, indentation is used only for expository=20
purposes.) </P>
<P>The "front" element consists of a "title" element, one or more =
"author"=20
elements, a "date" element, one or more optional "area" elements, one or =
more=20
optional "workgroup" elements, one or more optional "keyword" elements, =
an=20
optional "abstract" element. and, one or more optional "note" elements. =
</P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor3>2.2.1</A>&nbsp;The title Element</H4>
<P>The "title" element identifies the title of the document. Because the =
title=20
will be used in the headers of the document when formatted according to =
<A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#refs.RFC2223=
">[2]</A>,=20
if the title is more than 42 characters, then an abbreviation should =
also be=20
provided, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;title abbrev=3D"Much Ado about =
Nothing"&gt;
    The IETF's Discussion on "Source Format of RFC Documents"
    &lt;/title&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Dauthor>2.2.2</A>&nbsp;The author Element</H4>
<P>Each "author" element identifies a document author. Since a document =
may have=20
more than one author, more than one "author" element may be present. If =
the=20
author is a person, then three attributes must be present in the=20
"&lt;author&gt;" tag, "initials", "surname", and "fullname", e.g., =
</P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;author initials=3D"M.T." surname=3D"Rose"
            fullname=3D"Marshall T. Rose"&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "author" element itself consists of an "organization" element, =
and, an=20
optional "address" element. </P>
<P>The "organization" element is similar to the "title" element, in that =
an=20
abbreviation may be paired with a long organization name using the =
"abbrev"=20
attribute, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;organization abbrev=3D"ISI"&gt;
        USC/Information Sciences Institute
    &lt;/organization&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "address" element consists of an optional "postal" element, an =
optional=20
"phone" element, an optional "facsimile" element, an optional "email" =
element,=20
and, an optional "uri" element. </P>
<P>The "postal" element contains one or more "street" elements, followed =
by any=20
combination of "city", "region" (state or province), "code" (zipcode or =
postal=20
code), and "country" elements, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;postal&gt;
        &lt;street&gt;660 York Street&lt;/street&gt;
        &lt;street&gt;M/S 40&lt;/street&gt;
        &lt;city&gt;San Francisco&lt;/city&gt; =
&lt;region&gt;CA&lt;/region&gt;
        &lt;code&gt;94110&lt;/code&gt;
        &lt;country&gt;US&lt;/country&gt;
    &lt;/postal&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>This flexibility is provided to allow for different national formats =
for=20
postal addresses. Note however, that although the order of the "city", =
"region",=20
"code", and "country" elements isn't specified, at most one of each may =
be=20
present. Regardless, these elements must not be re-ordered during =
processing by=20
an XML application (e.g., display applications must preserve the =
ordering of the=20
information contained in these elements). Finally, the value of the =
"country"=20
element should be a two-letter code from ISO 3166. </P>
<P>The "phone", "facsimile", "email", and "uri" elements are simple, =
e.g.,=20
</P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;phone&gt;+1 415 695 3975&lt;/phone&gt;
    &lt;email&gt;mrose@not.invisible.net&lt;/email&gt;
    &lt;uri&gt;http://invisible.net/&lt;/uri&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Ddate>2.2.3</A>&nbsp;The date Element</H4>
<P>The "date" element identifies the publication date of the document. =
It=20
consists of a month and a year, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;date =
month=3D"February" year=3D"1999" /&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "date" element also has an optional day attribute. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor4>2.2.4</A>&nbsp;Meta Data Elements</H4>
<P>The "front" element may contain meta data -- the content of these =
elements=20
does not appear in printed versions of the document. </P>
<P>A document has one or more optional "area", "workgroup" and "keyword" =

elements, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;area&gt;General&lt;/area&gt;
    &lt;workgroup&gt;RFC Beautification Working Group&lt;/workgroup&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;RFC&lt;/keyword&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;Request for Comments&lt;/keyword&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;I-D&lt;/keyword&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;Internet-Draft&lt;/keyword&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;XML&lt;/keyword&gt;
    &lt;keyword&gt;Extensible Markup Language&lt;/keyword&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "area" elements identify a general category for the document =
(e.g., one=20
of "Applications", "General", "Internet", "Management", "Operations", =
"Routing",=20
"Security", "Transport", or "User"), while the "workgroup" elements =
identify the=20
IETF working groups that produced the document, and the "keyword" =
elements=20
identify useful search terms. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor5>2.2.5</A>&nbsp;The abstract Element</H4>
<P>A document may have an "abstract" element, which contains one or more =
<A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#t">"t" =
elements</A>.=20
In general, only a single "t" element is present, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE> =
   &lt;abstract&gt;
        &lt;t&gt;This memo presents a technique for using XML
        (Extensible Markup Language) as a source format
        for documents in the Internet-Drafts (I-Ds) and
        Request for Comments (RFC) series.&lt;/t&gt;
    &lt;/abstract&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Danchor6>2.2.6</A>&nbsp;The note Element</H4>
<P>A document may have one or more "note" elements, each of which =
contains one=20
or more <A =
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#t">"t"=20
elements</A>. There is a mandatory "title" attribute. In general, the =
"note"=20
element contains text from the IESG, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;note =
title=3D"IESG Note"&gt;
        &lt;t&gt;The IESG has something to say.&lt;/t&gt;
    &lt;/note&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Danchor7>2.2.7</A>&nbsp;Status, Copyright Notice, Table of=20
Contents</H4>
<P>Note that text relating to the memo's status, copyright notice, or =
table of=20
contents is not included in the document's markup -- this is =
automatically=20
inserted by an XML application when it produces either a text or HTML =
version of=20
the document. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dipr>2.2.7.1</A>&nbsp;Conformance with RFC 2026</H4>
<P>If an Internet-Draft is being produced, then the "ipr" attribute =
should be=20
present in the "&lt;rfc&gt;" tag at the beginning of the file. The value =
of the=20
attribute should be one of:=20
<BLOCKQUOTE class=3Dtext>
  <DL>
    <DT>full2026:=20
    <DD>indicating that the document is in full conformance with all the =

    provisions of Section 10 of RFC 2026;=20
    <DT>noDerivativeWorks2026:=20
    <DD>indicating that the document is in full conformance with all the =

    provisions of Section 10 of RFC 2026 except that the right to =
produce=20
    derivative works is not granted; or,=20
    <DT>none:=20
    <DD>indicating that the document is NOT offered in accordance with =
Section=20
    10 of RFC 2026, and the author does not provide the IETF with any =
rights=20
    other than to publish as an Internet-Draft. =
</DD></DL></BLOCKQUOTE>In the latter=20
case, a copyright notice will not be automatically inserted during =
processing by=20
an XML application.=20
<P></P>
<P>Consult <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#refs.RFC2026=
">[3]</A>=20
for further details. </P>
<P>Finally, if the Internet-Draft is being submitted to an automated =
process,=20
then the "docName" attribute should be present in the "&lt;rfc&gt;" tag =
at the=20
beginning of the file. The value of this attribute contains the document =
(not=20
file) name associated with this Internet-Draft, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>   =
 &lt;rfc ipr=3D"full" docName=3D"draft-mrose-writing-rfcs-01"&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/rfc&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P></P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor8>2.2.8</A>&nbsp;Everything in the Front</H4>
<P>So, putting it all together, we have, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    =
&lt;front&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;Writing I-Ds and RFCs using XML&lt;/title&gt;
   =20
        &lt;author initials=3D"M.T." surname=3D"Rose"
                fullname=3D"Marshall T. Rose"&gt;
            &lt;organization&gt;Invisible Worlds, =
Inc.&lt;/organization&gt;
   =20
            &lt;address&gt;
                &lt;postal&gt;
                    &lt;street&gt;660 York Street&lt;/street&gt;
                    &lt;street&gt;M/S 40&lt;/street&gt;
                    &lt;city&gt;San Francisco&lt;/city&gt; =
&lt;region&gt;CA&lt;/region&gt;
                    &lt;code&gt;94110&lt;/code&gt;
                    &lt;country&gt;US&lt;/country&gt;
                &lt;/postal&gt;
   =20
                &lt;phone&gt;+1 415 695 3975&lt;/phone&gt;
                &lt;email&gt;mrose@not.invisible.net&lt;/email&gt;
                &lt;uri&gt;http://invisible.net/&lt;/uri&gt;
            &lt;/address&gt;
        &lt;/author&gt;
   =20
        &lt;date month=3D"February" year=3D"1999" /&gt;
   =20
        &lt;area&gt;General&lt;/area&gt;
        &lt;workgroup&gt;RFC Beautification Working =
Group&lt;/workgroup&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;RFC&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;Request for Comments&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;I-D&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;Internet-Draft&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;XML&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;keyword&gt;Extensible Markup Language&lt;/keyword&gt;
        &lt;abstract&gt;
            &lt;t&gt;This memo presents a technique for using XML
            (Extensible Markup Language) as a source format
            for documents in the Internet-Drafts (I-Ds) and
            Request for Comments (RFC) series.&lt;/t&gt;
        &lt;/abstract&gt;
    &lt;/front&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Danchor9>2.3</A>&nbsp;The Middle</H4>
<P>The "middle" element contains all the sections of the document except =
for the=20
bibliography and appendices: </P></FONT><PRE>    ...
    &lt;/front&gt;
    &lt;middle&gt;
        &lt;section ...&gt;
        &lt;section ...&gt;
        &lt;section ...&gt;
    &lt;/middle&gt;
    &lt;back&gt;
    ...
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "middle" element consists of one or more "section" elements. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dsection>2.3.1</A>&nbsp;The section Element</H4>
<P>Each "section" element contains a section of the document. There is a =

mandatory attribute, "title", that identifies the title of the section. =
There is=20
also an optional attribute, "anchor", that is used for cross-referencing =
with <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xref">the =
"xref"=20
element</A>, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;section anchor=3D"intro" =
title=3D"Introduction"&gt;
        ...
    &lt;/section&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "section" element is recursive -- each contains any number and=20
combination of "t", "figure", and "section" elements, e.g., =
</P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;section title=3D"The Middle"&gt;
        ...
        &lt;section title=3D"The section Element"&gt;
            ...
            &lt;section title=3D"The t Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
            &lt;section title=3D"The list =
Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
            &lt;section title=3D"The figure =
Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
            &lt;section title=3D"The xref =
Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
            &lt;section title=3D"The eref =
Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
            &lt;section title=3D"The iref =
Element"&gt;...&lt;/section&gt;
        &lt;/section&gt;
    &lt;/section&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Dt>2.3.1.1</A>&nbsp;The t Element</H4>
<P>The "t" element contains any number and combination of paragraphs, =
lists, and=20
figures. If a cross-reference is needed to a section, figure, or =
reference, <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xref">the =
"xref"=20
element</A> is used; similarly, if an external-reference is needed, <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#eref">the =
"eref"=20
element</A> is used. Indexing of text is provided by the <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#iref">the =
"iref"=20
element</A>. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor10>2.3.1.2</A>&nbsp;The list Element</H4>
<P>The "list" element contains one or more items. Each item is a "t" =
element,=20
allowing for recursion, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;list =
style=3D"numbers"&gt;
        &lt;t&gt;The first item.&lt;/t&gt;
        &lt;t&gt;The second item, which contains two bulleted sub-items:
            &lt;list style=3D"symbols"&gt;
                &lt;t&gt;The first sub-item.&lt;/t&gt;
                &lt;t&gt;The second sub-item.&lt;/t&gt;
            &lt;/list&gt;
        &lt;/t&gt;
    &lt;/list&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "list" element has an optional attribute, "style", having the =
value=20
"numbers" (for numeric lists), "symbols" (for bulleted lists), "hanging" =
(for=20
hanging lists), or, "empty" (for indented text). If a "list" element is =
nested,=20
the default value is taken from its closest parent; otherwise, the =
default value=20
is "empty". </P>
<P>When nested within a "hanging list" element, the "t" element has an =
optional=20
attribute, "hangText" that specifies the text to be inserted, e.g., =
</P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;list style=3D"hanging"&gt;
        &lt;t hangText=3D"full2026:"&gt;indicating that the document is =
in
        full conformance with all the provisions of Section 10 of
        RFC 2026;&lt;/t&gt;

        &lt;t hangText=3D"noDerivativeWorks2026:"&gt;indicating that the
        document is in full conformance with all the provisions of
        Section 10 of RFC 2026 except that the right to produce
        derivative works is not granted; or,&lt;/t&gt;

        &lt;t hangText=3D"none:"&gt;indicating that the document is NOT
        offered in accordance with Section 10 of RFC 2026, and
        the author does not provide the IETF with any rights other
        than to publish as an Internet-Draft.&lt;/t&gt;
    &lt;/list&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<H4><A name=3Dfigure>2.3.1.3</A>&nbsp;The figure Element</H4>
<P>The "figure" element groups an optional "preamble" element, an =
"artwork"=20
element, and an optional "postamble" element together. The "figure" =
element also=20
has an optional "anchor" attribute that is used for cross-referencing =
with <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xref">the =
"xref"=20
element</A>. There is also an optional "title" attribute that identifies =
the=20
title of the figure. </P>
<P>The "preamble" and "postamble" elements, if present, are simply text. =
If a=20
cross-reference is needed to a section, figure, or reference, <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xref">the =
"xref"=20
element</A> is used; similarly, if an external-reference is needed, <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#eref">the =
"eref"=20
element</A> is used. Indexing of text is provided by the <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#iref">the =
"iref"=20
element</A>. </P>
<P>The "artwork" element, which must be present, contains "ASCII =
artwork".=20
Unlike text contained in the "t", "preamble", or "postamble" elements, =
both=20
horizontal and vertical whitespace is significant in the "artwork" =
element. </P>
<P>So, putting it all together, we have, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    =
&lt;figure anchor=3D"figure_example"&gt;
        &lt;preamble&gt;So,
        putting it all together, we have, e.g.,&lt;/preamble&gt;
        &lt;artwork&gt;
            ascii artwork goes here...
   =20
            be sure to use "&amp;lt;" or "&amp;amp;" instead of "&lt;" =
and "&amp;",
            respectively!
        &lt;/artwork&gt;
        &lt;postamble&gt;which is a very simple =
example.&lt;/postamble&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>which is a very simple example. </P>
<P>If you have artwork with a lot of "&lt;" characters, then there's an =
XML=20
trick you can use: </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;figure&gt;
        &lt;preamble&gt;If you have artwork with a lot of "&amp;lt;"
        characters, then there's an XML trick you can
        use:&lt;/preamble&gt;
        &lt;artwork&gt;&lt;![CDATA[
            ascii artwork goes here...
   =20
            just don't use "]]" in your artwork!
        ]]&gt;&lt;/artwork&gt;
        &lt;postamble&gt;The "&amp;lt;![CDATA[ ... ]]&gt;" construct is =
called
        a CDATA block -- everything between the innermost brackets
        is left alone by the XML application.&lt;/postamble&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "&lt;![CDATA[ ... ]]&gt;" construct is called a CDATA block -- =
everything=20
between the innermost brackets is left alone by the XML application. =
</P>
<P>Because the "figure" element represents a logical grouping of text =
and=20
artwork, an XML application producing a text version of the document =
should=20
attempt to keep these elements on the same page. Because <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#refs.RFC2223=
">RFC=20
2223</A>[2] allows no more than 69 characters by 49 lines of content on =
each=20
page, XML applications should be prepared to prematurely introduce page =
breaks=20
to allow for better visual grouping. </P>
<P>Finally, the "artwork" element has two optional attributes: "name" =
and=20
"type". The former is used to suggest a filename to use when storing the =
content=20
of the "artwork" element, whilst the latter contains a suggestive =
data-typing=20
for the content. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dxref>2.3.1.4</A>&nbsp;The xref Element</H4>
<P>The "xref" element is used to cross-reference sections, figures, and=20
references. The mandatory "target" attribute is used to link back to the =

"anchor" attribute of the "section", "figure", and "reference" elements. =
The=20
value of the "anchor" and "target" attributes should be formatted =
according to=20
the token syntax in <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xml_basics">=
XML=20
basics</A>. </P>
<P>If used as an empty element, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    according to =
the token syntax in &lt;xref target=3D"xml_basics" /&gt;.
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>then the XML application inserts an appropriate phrase during =
processing,=20
such as "Section 2.1" or "&lt;a href=3D"#xml_basics"&gt;XML =
Basics&lt;/a&gt;".=20
</P>
<P>If used with content, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    conforming to =
&lt;xref target=3D"refs.RFC2223"&gt;RFC 2223&lt;/xref&gt;.
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>then the XML application inserts an appropriate designation during=20
processing, such as "RFC 2223[2]" or "&lt;a =
href=3D"#refs.RFC2223"&gt;RFC=20
2223&lt;/a&gt;". Although the XML application decides what "an =
appropriate=20
designation" might be, its choice is consistent throughout the =
processing of the=20
document. </P>
<H4><A name=3Deref>2.3.1.5</A>&nbsp;The eref Element</H4>
<P>The "eref" element is used to reference external documents. The =
mandatory=20
"target" attribute is a <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#URI">URI</A>=
[4],=20
e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;eref =
target=3D"http://metalab.unc.edu/xml/"&gt;Cafe con Leche&lt;/eref&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>Note that while the "target" attribute is always present, the "eref" =
element=20
may be empty, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;eref =
target=3D"http://invisible.net/" /&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>and the XML application inserts an appropriate designation during =
processing=20
such as "[9]" or "&lt;a=20
href=3D"http://invisible.net/"&gt;http://invisible.net/&lt;/a&gt;". </P>
<H4><A name=3Diref>2.3.1.6</A>&nbsp;The iref Element</H4>
<P><A name=3Danchor22></A>The "iref" element is used to add information =
to an=20
index. The mandatory "item" attribute is the primary key the information =
is=20
stored under, whilst the optional "subitem" attribute is the secondary =
key,=20
e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;iref item=3D"indexing" subitem=3D"how to" =
/&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>Finally, note that the "iref" element is always empty -- it never =
contains=20
any text. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor11>2.3.1.7</A>&nbsp;The vspace Element</H4>
<P>The "vspace" element, which may occur only inside the "t" element, is =
used by=20
the author to provide formatting guidance to the XML application. There =
is an=20
attribute, "blankLines", that indicates the number of blank lines that =
should be=20
inserted. A physical linebreak is specified by using the default value, =
"0".=20
</P>
<P>In addition, the "vspace" element can be used to force a new physical =

paragraph within a list item, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;list =
style=3D"numbers"&gt;
        &lt;t&gt;This is list item.
           &lt;vspace blankLines=3D"1" /&gt;
           This is part of the same list item,
           although when displayed, it appears
           as a separate physical paragraph.&lt;/t&gt;
    &lt;/list&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>An XML application producing a text version of the document should =
exercise=20
care when encountering a value for "blankLines" that causes a pagebreak =
-- in=20
particular, if a "vspace" element causes a pagebreak, then no further =
blank=20
lines should be inserted. This allows authors to "force" a pagebreak by =
using an=20
arbitrarily large value, e.g., "blankLines=3D'100'". </P>
<P>Finally, note that the "vspace" element is always empty -- it never =
contains=20
any text. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dback_matter>2.4</A>&nbsp;Back matter</H4>
<P>Finally, the "back" element is used for references and appendices:=20
</P></FONT><PRE>        ...
        &lt;/middle&gt;
        &lt;back&gt;
            &lt;references&gt;
                &lt;reference ...&gt;
                &lt;reference ...&gt;
            &lt;/references&gt;
            &lt;section ...&gt;
            &lt;section ...&gt;
        &lt;/back&gt;
    &lt;/rfc&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "back" element consists of an optional "references" element, and, =
one or=20
more optional "section" elements. The "back" element itself is optional, =
if your=20
document doesn't have any references or appendices, you don't have to =
include=20
it. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dreferences>2.4.1</A>&nbsp;The references Element</H4>
<P>The "references" element contains the document's bibliography. It =
contains=20
one or more "reference" elements. </P>
<P>Each "reference" element contains a "front" element and one or more =
optional=20
"seriesInfo" elements. </P>
<P>We've already discussed the "front" element back in <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#front_matter=
">Front=20
matter</A>. </P>
<P>The "seriesInfo" element has two attributes, "name" and "value" that =
identify=20
the document series and series entry, respectively. </P>
<P>The "reference" element has an optional "anchor" attribute that is =
used for=20
cross-referencing with <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xref">the =
"xref"=20
element</A>, e.g., </P></FONT><PRE>    &lt;reference =
anchor=3D"refs.RFC2200"&gt;
        &lt;front&gt;
            &lt;title&gt;Internet Official Protocol =
Standards&lt;/title&gt;
            &lt;author initials=3D"J." surname=3D"Postel"
                    fullname=3D"Jon Postel"&gt;
                &lt;organization abbrev=3D"ISI"&gt;
                USC/Information Sciences Institute
                &lt;/organization&gt;
            &lt;/author&gt;
   =20
            &lt;date month=3D"June" year=3D"1997" /&gt;
        &lt;/front&gt;
        &lt;seriesInfo name=3D"RFC" value=3D"2200" /&gt;
        &lt;seriesInfo name=3D"STD" value=3D"1" /&gt;
    &lt;/reference&gt;
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>The "reference" element also has an optional "target" attribute that =
is used=20
for external references (c.f., <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#eref">The =
eref=20
Element</A>). The XML application, if producing an HTML version of the =
document=20
will use the "target" attribute accordingly; however, if the "name" =
attribute of=20
the "seriesInfo" element has the value "RFC", then the XML application =
should=20
automatically provide an appropriate default for the "target" attribute =
(e.g.,=20
"http://example.com/rfcs/rfc2200.txt"). </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor12>2.4.2</A>&nbsp;Appendices</H4>
<P>To include appendices after the bibliography, simply add more =
"section"=20
elements. (For an example, look at the example at the beginning of <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#back_matter"=
>Back=20
matter</A>.) </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor13>2.4.3</A>&nbsp;Copyright Status</H4>
<P>The copyright status for the document is not included in the =
document's=20
markup -- this is automatically inserted by an XML application that =
produces=20
either a text or HTML version of the document. </P><A =
name=3Danchor14><BR>
<HR SIZE=3D1 shade=3D"0">
</A>
