<H3>3.&nbsp;Processing the XML Source File</H3>
<P>This section concerns itself with applications that operate on an XML =
source=20
file. A lot of XML tools are available, as are many lists of XML =
resources,=20
e.g., <A href=3D"http://metalab.unc.edu/xml/">Cafe con Leche</A>. </P>
<P>There are two kinds of XML tools: validating and non-validating. Both =
check=20
that the source file conforms to the rules given in <A=20
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/writing-rfcs.html#xml_basics">=
XML=20
basics</A>. However, in addition to making sure that the source file is=20
well-formed, a validating tool also reads the DTD referenced by the =
source file=20
to make sure that they match. There are a number of both validating and=20
non-validating tools available. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor15>3.1</A>&nbsp;Editing</H4>
<P>There are several XML editors available. Ideally, you want an editor =
that=20
validates. This has two advantages:=20
<UL class=3Dtext>
  <LI>the editor provides guidance in fleshing-out the document =
structure; and,=20
  <LI>the editor validates that the source file matches the rules in the =
DTD.=20
  </LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>There are two major modes in Emacs that support XML: <A=20
href=3D"http://www.mulberrytech.com/tdtd/">tdtd</A> and <A=20
href=3D"http://www.inria.fr/koala/plh/sxml.html">psgml</A>. The latter =
mode allows=20
you to validate the source file (by calling an external program). If you =
visit=20
the source file in Emacs and the major mode isn't "SGML" or "XML", then =
usually=20
all it takes is adding these lines to your ".emacs" file: =
</P></FONT><PRE>    (setq auto-mode-alist
          (cons (cons "\\.xml$" 'sgml-mode) auto-mode-alist))
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>and then restarting Emacs. If this doesn't work, try one of the =
sources=20
above. </P>
<P>The author uses both sgml-mode in Emacs, and a commercial validating =
editor,=20
<A href=3D"http://www.t2000-usa.com/">Clip! version 1.5</A>, when =
editing source=20
files. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor16>3.1.1</A>&nbsp;Checking</H4>
<P>If your editor doesn't validate, then you should run a program to =
validate=20
the source file. </P>
<P>The author uses <A =
href=3D"http://www.alphaworks.ibm.com/formula/xml/">the=20
AlphaWorks XML parser</A> for this purpose. It requires that your system =
have a=20
Java virtual machine. In addition to Java, there are validating parsers =
written=20
in C, Perl, Python, and Tcl. </P>
<H4><A name=3Dxml2rfc>3.2</A>&nbsp;Converting to Text Format</H4>
<P>The author has written <A =
href=3D"http://memory.palace.org/authoring/">the=20
xml2rfc tool</A>, which reads the source file and produces both a text =
and HTML=20
version of the document. (This memo was produced using the xml2rfc =
tool.) Note=20
that xml2rfc isn't a validating tool, so it's a good idea to use either =
a=20
validating editor or run a stand-alone validating parser prior to using =
the=20
tool. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor17>3.3</A>&nbsp;Converting to HTML Format</H4>
<P>The XML Style Language (XSL) is used to describe transformations from =
the=20
source file into some other structured file. So, ideally you should use =
an=20
XSL-capable formatter to convert an XML source file to HTML. </P>
<P>However, as of this writing XSL is still in considerable flux. =
(Hence, no=20
reference was included in this memo, as by the time you read this =
section, the=20
reference would be outdated.) So, in the interim, the author uses the =
xml2rfc=20
tool for this purpose, even though this tool doesn't provide much =
flexibility in=20
its HTML layout. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor18>3.4</A>&nbsp;Viewing</H4>
<P>Browsers that support either XSL or Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) are =
able to=20
view the source file directly. </P>
<P>At present, the author doesn't use any of these browsers, instead =
converting=20
source files to either text or HTML. </P>
<H4><A name=3Danchor19>3.5</A>&nbsp;Searching</H4>
<P>As with text editors, any text-oriented search tool (e.g., grep) can =
be used=20
on the source file. However, there are search tools available that =
understand=20
structured source. </P>
<P>The author uses <A=20
href=3D"http://www.cs.helsinki.fi/~jjaakkol/sgrep.html">sgrep version =
1.9</A> for=20
this purpose, e.g. </P></FONT><PRE>    sgrep -g xml 'ELEMENTS("title") =
not in ELEMENTS("back")' \
        writing-rfcs.xml
</PRE><FONT face=3D"verdana, helvetica, arial, sans-serif" size=3D2>
<P>which extracts the title element from the source file. </P><A=20
name=3Danchor20><BR>
<HR SIZE=3D1 shade=3D"0">
</A>
